Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
10:09 AM; Case called for Hearing.  Defendant Tina D Daniels not in court.  Attorney Peter M Wolff in court for Tina D Daniels.  Prosecuting attorney Peter Michael Tempelis in court for the State of Wisconsin. Court notes the matter was last in court on 10/05/2022 and the defendant did not appear so the court stayed a capias until today's date.  Atty. Wolff advises he has not heard from his client today, but notes the defendant was in the hospital but has not received any verification from his client.  Atty. Wolff advises he last spoke with her a day or 2 after the 10/05/2022 hearing and her family was supposed to get him verification of the hospitalization.  Atty. Wolff requests the court to stay the capias for 1 more week to allow him to obtain the medical verification and his client to appear.  Atty. Wolff confirms his client was aware of the hearing.  State requests the capias be issued.  Atty. Wolff notes that he is in this court this Friday at 10:00 and inquires if the court will stay the capias until then.  Court will continue to stay the issuance of a capias and adjourn this matter for further proceedings to this Friday.

Court notes at 10:13 a.m. Defendant Tina D Daniels appeared in court; all other appearances remain the same.  Court inquires why the defendant did not appear at the last hearing on 10/05/2022.  Defendant responds.  Court will not issue the capias.  Atty. Wolff provides an update; he is requesting one more further proceedings in about 30 days.  No objection by the State.  Court adjourns for further proceedings.
Hearing scheduled for November 14, 2022 at 10:30 am.

3:43 PM; Case called for Hearing.  Defendant Tina D Daniels not in court.  Attorney Peter M Wolff in court for Tina D Daniels.  Prosecuting attorney Christian Farina in court for the State of Wisconsin. Atty. Wolff advises he has no explanation for his client's non-appearance but is asking the court to stay the issuance of a warrant.  State has no objection to a capias being stayed as this is the defendant's first missed appearance.  Court will authorize but stay the issuance of a capias and adjourn to next week for status.
Hearing scheduled for October 12, 2022 at 10:00 am.
